According to your comments it is a DTO and not a managed entity for JPA. Ditch the annotations and add a getter/setter for each property.

```java
public class GetList {

    private int id;
    private int t2Id;

    public void setId(int id) { this.id=id;}
    public int getId() { return this.id;}
    public void setT2Id(int t2Id) { this.t2Id=t2Id;}
    public int getT2Id() { return this.t2Id;}

    public void hashCode() {
        return Objects.hashCode(this.id, this.t2Id);
    }

    public void equals(Object other) {
        if (other instanceof GetList) {
            GetList that = (GetList) other;
            return this.id == that.id &amp;&amp; this.t2Id == that.t2Id;
        } 
        return false;
    }
}
```

Spring Data JPA will now use this as a projection and not a managed entity.

